<DOC><DOCNO> AP890815-0166 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1918EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-NorthAppeal     08-15 0145</FIRST><SECOND>AM-North Appeal,140</SECOND><HEAD>Court Will Hear North's Appeal Next February</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Oliver North's appeal of his convictions in theIran-Contra scandal will be heard next Feb. 6 before a three-memberpanel of judges.   Reviewing the North case will be U.S. Court of Appeals judgesAbner Mikva, Laurence Silberman and David Sentelle, according to anotice issued by the court.   Mikva is a Carter administration appointee while Silberman andSentelle were appointed during the Reagan administration.   The court notice was signed last week and made available Tuesday.   North was convicted May 4 of aiding and abetting an obstructionof Congress, destruction of National Security Council documents andaccepting an illegal gratuity.   He was fined $150,000, given two years probation and ordered toserve 1,200 hours of community service.   He has decided to proceed with the community service whileappealing the three felony convictions.</TEXT></DOC>